{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618234"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16502"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16502"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0.91,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65514"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9193"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50953"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10320"},{"type":"tags","id":"10326"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65514"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETwo-point discrimination is an important clinical test used to assess tactile spatial acuity in different regions of the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the two-point discrimination threshold?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mean distance between two points that can be detected","Maximum distance between two points that can be detected","Smallest distance between two points that can be consciously perceived as separate","Distance between two points that can be unconsciously detected","Time interval needed to distinguish between two separate points"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esmallest distance between two points that can be consciously perceived as separate\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct definition of two-point discrimination threshold. This measurement reflects the density of mechanoreceptors in the skin and their corresponding cortical representation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMean distance between two points that can be detected\u003C/strong\u003E - The threshold is specifically the minimum, not an average distance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximum distance between two points that can be detected\u003C/strong\u003E - The threshold represents the minimum, not maximum distance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistance between two points that can be unconsciously detected\u003C/strong\u003E - Two-point discrimination requires conscious perception\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETime interval needed to distinguish between two separate points\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes temporal discrimination rather than spatial discrimination\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo-point discrimination varies significantly across body regions, with areas like fingertips showing much finer discrimination than areas like the back, reflecting differences in receptor density and cortical representation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Two-point discrimination threshold is the minimum distance at which two simultaneously applied stimuli can be perceived as separate points rather than one.","Two-point discrimination varies across different body regions, with fingertips having much better discrimination (2-3 mm) than the back (\u003E40 mm).","This measurement reflects the density of sensory receptors and corresponding cortical representation of different body regions."],"references":["Tong J, Mao O, Goldreich D. Two-point orientation discrimination versus the traditional two-point test for tactile spatial acuity assessment. Front Hum Neurosci. 2013 Sep 13;7:579. doi: 10.3389/fnhum.2013.00579. PMID: 24062677; PMCID: PMC3772339.","Won SY, Kim HK, Kim ME, Kim KS. Two-point discrimination values vary depending on test site, sex and test modality in the orofacial region: a preliminary study. J Appl Oral Sci. 2017 Jul-Aug;25(4):427-435. doi: 10.1590/1678-7757-2016-0462. PMID: 28877282; PMCID: PMC5595116.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50953"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50953"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:07:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:54:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9193"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65514"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"dat